56121251.body:
(cross-posted from https://spectrum.chat/apollo/react-apollo/firing-query-in-response-to-user-input-e-g-onclick~13ae09a8-6028-48cf-ac3f-3fbba2307ccc)

I've spent the afternoon beating my head against what I think should be a fairly straightforward task: firing a query in response to user input; for example, a search field.

I have an app that accepts user input in a search field. I need to make a query, setting a variable to the value of that field, when the user clicks the "search" button. The query needs to be set to network-only so that it fetches fresh data each time. When the query completes, I need to display a detail component that displays the data fetched from the server. That detail view contains a couple of <Mutation /> components that make updates to the user's data. The detail view needs to stay in sync so that it reflects the current state.

I've tried a couple of approaches to this, and each one gets me part way there, but not all the way. I'm sure I'm missing something simple.

Approach 1: <Query /> Component

The top-level app component looks something like this (simplified from the actual):

const App = () => {
  const [searchFieldValue, setSearchFieldValue] = useState('');
  const [username, setUsername] = useState('');
  return (
    <Container>
      <Input
        placeholder="Username"
        name="username"
        id="username"
        value={searchFieldValue}
        width={6}
        onChange={(e, { value }) => {
          setSearchFieldValue(value);
        }}
        />
        <Button onClick={ () => { 
          setUsername(searchFieldInput)
        }>Search</Button>

        {username && <DetailView username={username} />
    </Container>
}

const DetailView = ({username}) => (
  <Query query={GET_USER} variables={{username}} fetchPolicy="network-only">
    {({data, loading, error}) => {
      if (loading) return <Loading />
      if (error) return <Error />
      const { user } = data;
      return (
      // display user data
      // includes a couple of buttons that trigger mutations on the user
      )
    }}
  </Query>
)


In essence, when the "search" button is clicked, I set the username state variable to the content of the search field. This causes username to no longer be falsey, and the DetailView component is mounted.

What works:

The query is sent to the server the, data is received and stored in the cache, and the view is rendered. The mutations all work properly, and the cache is updated with their outcome. If I enter a different value in the search input, this causes <App />'s state to change and re-render; the child Query is re-rendered, and a new query is sent, etc.

What doesn't work:

I can't search for the same user twice. For example, let's say I enter "janesmith" in the search field. I get Jane's information and the <DetailView /> is rendered. If I want to re-fetch Jane's details by clicking the search button again, nothing happens, because <App />'s state hasn't actually changed.

I know that I can render a control as a child of the Query inside DetailView and have it trigger the refetch function, but that's not what I want - I want the search button to fire the query every time.

One possible workaround I've considered is converting App to a Class component, and having the search button's click handler do something like `this.setState({username: null}, () => { this.setState({ username: searchFieldInput} )}), which should trigger a re-render, but this seems incredibly hacky.

Approach 2: <ApolloConsumer /> and firing query() manually

The react-apollo docs on queries suggest that for manually firing a query in response to user input, one should use ApolloConsumer and call client.query() manually in the click handler:

const App = () => {
  const [searchFieldValue, setSearchFieldValue] = useState('');
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  return (
    <ApolloConsumer>
      {client => (
        <Container>
        <Input
          placeholder="Username"
          name="username"
          id="username"
          value={searchFieldValue}
          width={6}
          onChange={(e, { value }) => {
            setSearchFieldValue(value);
          }}
          />
        <Button onClick={async () => { 
          const data = await client.query({
            query: GET_USER,
            variables: {
              username: searchFieldValue
            },
            fetchPolicy='network-only'
          })
          setUser(data.user);
        }>Search</Button>

        {user && <DetailView user={user} setUser={setUser} />
        </Container>
      )}
    </ApolloConsumer>
  )
}

const DetailView = ({user, setUser}) => (
  // .... render the user detail
  // includes a couple of <Mutation /> components that modify the user
  // These need to have the setUser function passed down to them so that they can update the state in <App />
)


What works:

When the search button is clicked, the query is sent to the server. The result is returned, and is stored in the cache. However there is no way to use the cache value in <DetailView /> in this case; the result has to be stored in state and passed down.

Because the query is being fired imperatively in the onClick handler, I can search for the same value over and over and it will send the queries to the server (due to the network-only fetch policy).

What doesn't work:

Although the mutations in DetailView work, and the cache is updated when they return, the UI does not update because it is the result of <App />'s state object. This means that in order to have the UI react to the result of the mutations, I need to pass my setUser function down through the props of all the children of DetailView (where the mutations live), and call setUser in the onCompleted handler of the mutations. This should work, but seems like a lot of unnecessary work. Also, I can't easily react to the loading and error states when calling client.query() imperatively.

One thing I've considered, but haven't tried, is a combination of both imperative and declarative: wrap <App /> in <ApolloConsumer> and fire the query manually in the button's onClick handler with a network-only fetch policy, and have the DetailView component render a <Query/> component for the same query, but with a cache-only fetch policy. Again, this seems overly cumbersome.

Like I said, I'm sure I'm missing something extremely simple, but I can't see what it is. Any help would be greatly appreciated. Thanks!

